        public boolean isOrderStarted(Order order)

        1) it is not completed 2) car assigned has already moved from starting city or cargo has been already loaded to that car
        Parameters:
        order - order to check
        Returns:
        true if order has been started, false otherwise

      • findAppropriateCarAndDriversAndCalculatePath

        public Object[] findAppropriateCarAndDriversAndCalculatePath(List<RoutePoint> list,
                                                             List<CityDistance> distances,
                                                             List<City> cities)
        Calculates optimal path and attempts to select car and drivers to complete the order. Optimal path calculation is basically solving the "Traveling Salesman Problem" with additional restrictions, such as:
        City of unloading for cargo X can not be visited before city of loading for cargo X;
        Only loading cities can be starting points;
        Avoid starting from city cycles (that means that city X is city both for loading and unloading come cargo) at all costs;
        In common case we have open version of TSP (no need to return back to starting city), if not specified directly.
        All restrictions above are based on three reasons: 1) to avoid infinite loops during calculation 2) to make found routes applicable to the cause 3) to save extra time (the guesses are hypothetical and not proved mathematically)
        Parameters:
        list - list of RoutePoint entities
        distances - list of all CityDistance entities from database
        cities - list of all City entities.
        Returns:
        Object array of size 3: Object[0] is selected Car, Object[1] is List<User (selected drivers), Object[3] is String (shortest path, cities are divided by ";"), Object[4] is Float (required capacity, used in showing error message). Path and required capacity are never null.
        See Also:
        Traveling salesman problem

      • getShortestPath

        private int getShortestPath(int[][] matr,
                            List<Integer> result,
                            int from,
                            int to)
        Implementation of Dijkstra algorithm to find shortest path between to vertices in graph. Used for calculating paths between cities which are not connected directly.
        Parameters:

        result - list which will store shortest path indexes
        from - index of city to start from
        to - index of city to end at
        Returns:
        distance length, path is stored in result variable

      • findOptimalPathUsingAnnealingImitation

        private int[] findOptimalPathUsingAnnealingImitation(int[][] matr,
                                                     double initialTemperature,
                                                     double endTemperature,
                                                     int from,
                                                     List<Integer> loadingCities,
                                                     List<Integer> unloadingCities,
                                                     boolean cycleDetected)
        Simulated annealing algorithm implementation for solving the traveling salesman problem. This is modified version of algorithm based on some restrictions stated here
        Parameters:
        matr - matrix of distances between cities
        initialTemperature - temperature at which annealing starts
        endTemperature - temperature at which annealing ends
        from - city index to start from
        loadingCities - cities of loading cargo
        unloadingCities - cities of unloading cargo
        cycleDetected - flag if suggested path has cycles
        Returns:
        array of city indexes containing optimal path
        See Also:
        Simulated annealing algorithm
